    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen a help file tag has a double quote (\"), `:help {tag}` fails to open the tag.\n\nNotes: `K` works within the help file for tags with double quotes, also the tags with double quotes appear in the command-line completion. The issue is when trying to open the tag, so when executing `:help`.\n\nUse case: For a plugin I'd like to add a help tag with a a Lua table path, so the tag is something like:\n\n```\n*testhelptags.config.plug[\"<Plug>(DoStuff)\"].opts123*\n```\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Create a directory having only this file: `doc/testhelptags.txt`:\n\n```text\n|testhelptags-foo123|\n|testhelptags-\"bar123\"|\n|testhelptags.config.plug[\"<Plug>(DoStuff)\"].opts123|\n\n*testhelptags-foo123*\n\n*testhelptags-\"bar123\"*\n\n*testhelptags.config.plug[\"<Plug>(DoStuff)\"].opts123*\n\nvim:tw=78:ts=8:noet:ft=help:norl:\n```\n\n2. Run `:helptags {path/to/doc}` so the help tags are generated.\n\n3. In the dir created in step 1 run `nvim --clean -c 'let &rtp.=\",\".getcwd()'`\n\n4. `:help testhelptags.config.plug[\"<Plug>(DoStuff)\"].opts123`\n\n    or `:help testhelptags-\"bar123\"`\n\n**Actual behavior:**\n\n```text\nE149: No help for testhelptags.config.plug[\"<Plug>(DoStuff)\"].opts123\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe help file opens in the tag position.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.13.0-dev-601+gd214c24129\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nYes, 9.2.478\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS 26.3\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nkitty 0.47.0\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-kitty\n\n### Installation\n\nmise-en-place",
